      <hedline>
        <hl1>Civil Unions And Marriage</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Linda Baulsir letter on April 1 editorial on issue of homosexual marriages and civil unions in Connecticut</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Separate but Equal in Marriage'' (editorial, April 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Separate but Equal in Marriage'' (editorial, April 1):</p>
        <p>The sacraments of marriage are not civil issues but religious ones. The state should not be concerned with who marries whom. Its only concern is that of civil union. Protecting economic rights, inheritance rights, dissolution of partnerships -- those issues covered by contract law.</p>
        <p>Connecticut could lead the nation in recasting the debate. Everyone -- whatever their sexual orientation -- who wanted to enter into a lifelong committed relationship could go to their Town or City Hall and get a civil union license. If they then wanted to further commit to the religious sacraments of marriage, they could just go to their clergy and participate in the ceremonies and rituals of their faith.</p>
        <p>A minister, priest or rabbi should not have to say ''by the authority invested in me by the State of Connecticut I now pronounce you husband and wife.''</p>
        <p>Linda Baulsir  Brookfield</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
